## 2. Route Path Derivation

Model name → route path: lowercase the name, then naively pluralize by appending `s` (or `es` for names ending in `s`, `x`, `z`, `ch`, `sh`). Since there is no approved `pluralize` dependency in this new package yet, implement a minimal inline pluralizer rather than pulling in the `pluralize` npm package (which is already a dep of `client-generator-ts` — but we explicitly want a minimal dep tree here).

Algorithm:

```
User      → /users
Post      → /posts
Category  → /categorys   ← acceptable for a REST stub generator; note below
```

A more complete rule set (inline, no dep):

```
ends with 's'|'x'|'z'    → append 'es'   (e.g. Box → boxes)
ends with 'ch'|'sh'       → append 'es'   (e.g. Witch → witches)
ends with 'y' (not vowel) → replace 'y' with 'ies'  (e.g. Category → categories)
everything else            → append 's'
```

Function:

```typescript
// src/utils.ts
export function modelNameToRoute(modelName: string): string
// "User"     → "users"
// "Category" → "categories"
// "Box"      → "boxes"
```

---

## 3. Shape of Each Generated Output File

### 3a. `types.ts`

Contains one TypeScript `interface` per model (a flat "row" type using only scalar/enum fields — no relation fields) and one `type` string-union per enum.

```typescript
// GENERATED — do not edit manually
// Generated by @prisma/rest-client-generator

export type Role = 'ADMIN' | 'USER' | 'GUEST'

export interface User {
  id: number          // Int, isId=true
  email: string       // String
  name: string | null // String, isRequired=false → nullable
  role: Role          // enum
  createdAt: string   // DateTime
}

export interface Post {
  id: number
  title: string
  published: boolean
  authorId: number    // scalar FK field; relation object field "author" is excluded
}
```

Rules for `types.ts` model interface fields:
- Include fields where `kind === 'scalar'` or `kind === 'enum'`
- Exclude fields where `kind === 'object'` (relations)
- Exclude fields where `kind === 'unsupported'`
- If `field.isRequired === false`, append `| null` to the TypeScript type
- If `field.isList === true`, wrap the type in `Array<...>` (rare for scalars but handle it)

### 3b. `<ModelName>.ts` (one per model)

Contains three input interfaces and one client class.

#### Deriving `WhereUniqueInput`

Include only fields where `field.isId === true` OR `field.isUnique === true`, with `kind === 'scalar'`. All fields in `WhereUniqueInput` are required (they are the lookup keys). If `model.primaryKey` is non-null and lists composite key fields, include each of those fields too.

```typescript
export interface UserWhereUniqueInput {
  id: number
  // if email has @unique:
  email?: string
}
```

Since Prisma's generated `WhereUniqueInput` uses `@unique` as optional alternates, mirror that: `id` is required, additional `@unique` fields are `?:`.

Simpler rule: the `isId` field is required, all additional `isUnique` fields are optional.

#### Deriving `CreateInput`

Include all fields where `kind === 'scalar'` or `kind === 'enum'`:
- If `field.hasDefaultValue === true` OR `field.isUpdatedAt === true` OR `field.isGenerated === true`: mark as optional (`?:`)
- If `field.isRequired === false`: mark as optional and type is `T | null`
- If `field.isRequired === true` and no default: required

Exclude relation (`kind === 'object'`) fields entirely — this generator intentionally produces flat REST inputs.

```typescript
export interface UserCreateInput {
  email: string          // required, no default
  name?: string | null   // isRequired=false
  role?: Role            // hasDefaultValue=true (e.g. @default(USER))
  // id is excluded: isId=true AND hasDefaultValue=true (autoincrement)
}
```

For `id` fields: if `hasDefaultValue === true` (autoincrement, cuid, uuid, etc.) → optional in create.

#### Deriving `UpdateInput`

All fields are optional. Same scalar/enum filter as `CreateInput`. Type becomes `T | null` for nullable fields, plain `T` for required fields — but the property itself is always `?:`.

```typescript
export interface UserUpdateInput {
  email?: string
  name?: string | null
  role?: Role
}
```

#### Client class

The class name is `<ModelName>RestClient`. Constructor takes a `baseUrl: string`. Methods:

```typescript
export class UserRestClient {
  constructor(private readonly baseUrl: string) {}

  async findMany(): Promise<User[]>
  async findUnique(where: UserWhereUniqueInput): Promise<User | null>
  async create(data: UserCreateInput): Promise<User>
  async update(where: UserWhereUniqueInput, data: UserUpdateInput): Promise<User>
  async delete(where: UserWhereUniqueInput): Promise<User>
}
```

HTTP conventions used:
- `findMany` → `GET /users`
- `findUnique` → `GET /users/:id` (uses the first `isId` field value from `where`)
- `create` → `POST /users` with JSON body
- `update` → `PATCH /users/:id` with JSON body
- `delete` → `DELETE /users/:id`

The `id` segment is `String(where[idField])` where `idField` is the first `isId===true` field name.

Implementation uses the global `fetch` API (Node.js 18+, no extra dep).

Full annotated example for `User.ts`:

```typescript
// GENERATED — do not edit manually
// Generated by @prisma/rest-client-generator

import type { User } from './types'

export interface UserWhereUniqueInput {
  id: number
}

export interface UserCreateInput {
  email: string
  name?: string | null
  role?: Role
}

export interface UserUpdateInput {
  email?: string
  name?: string | null
  role?: Role
}

export class UserRestClient {
  constructor(private readonly baseUrl: string) {}

  private get base(): string {
    return `${this.baseUrl}/users`
  }

  async findMany(): Promise<User[]> {
    const res = await fetch(this.base)
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`GET ${this.base} failed: ${res.status}`)
    return res.json() as Promise<User[]>
  }

  async findUnique(where: UserWhereUniqueInput): Promise<User | null> {
    const url = `${this.base}/${encodeURIComponent(String(where.id))}`
    const res = await fetch(url)
    if (res.status === 404) return null
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`GET ${url} failed: ${res.status}`)
    return res.json() as Promise<User>
  }

  async create(data: UserCreateInput): Promise<User> {
    const res = await fetch(this.base, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(data),
    })
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`POST ${this.base} failed: ${res.status}`)
    return res.json() as Promise<User>
  }

  async update(where: UserWhereUniqueInput, data: UserUpdateInput): Promise<User> {
    const url = `${this.base}/${encodeURIComponent(String(where.id))}`
    const res = await fetch(url, {
      method: 'PATCH',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(data),
    })
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`PATCH ${url} failed: ${res.status}`)
    return res.json() as Promise<User>
  }

  async delete(where: UserWhereUniqueInput): Promise<User> {
    const url = `${this.base}/${encodeURIComponent(String(where.id))}`
    const res = await fetch(url, { method: 'DELETE' })
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`DELETE ${url} failed: ${res.status}`)
    return res.json() as Promise<User>
  }
}
```

### 3c. `index.ts`

Re-exports everything from `types.ts` and each `<ModelName>.ts`:

```typescript
// GENERATED — do not edit manually
export * from './types'
export * from './User'
export * from './Post'
```

